statement.p:
         What congruence class is indicated by the set:


\left\{\dots, -6, -1, 4, 9, 14, \dots\right\} 

\left\{\dots, -13, 20, 53, 86, \dots \right\}

solution.p:
There are a total of five congruence classes modulo 5:



    [0]_5 = \{ \dots, -5, 0, 5, 10, \dots \}



    [1]_5 = \{ \dots, -4, 1, 6, 11, \dots \}



    [2]_5 = \{ \dots, -3, 2, 7, 12, \dots \}



    [3]_5 = \{ \dots, -2, 3, 8, 13, \dots \}



    [4]_5 = \{ \dots, -1, 4, 9, 14, \dots \}



In general, there will always be m distinct congruence classes modulo m.

statement.p:
         Suppose that a \and b are integers, a \equiv 4 \pmod{13} and b \equiv 9\pmod{13}. Find the integer c with 0 \le c \le 12 such that:


c \equiv 9a \pmod{13} 

c \equiv 11b \pmod{13} 

c \equiv a+b \pmod{13} 

c \equiv a^2 + b^2 \pmod{13} 

c \equiv a^2 - b^2 \pmod{13}
